{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600581/1930101401/0733.xml":{"full_text":"B-14\nCITIZENS HAY\nSTUDENT HAZING\nv\nNortheast Group Also De\nplore Lack of Books in\nPublic Schools.\nRazing in the ranks of students in\nthe District schools was flayed before\nthe meeting of the Northeast Washing\nton Citizens* Association at the Ludlow\nSchool last night.\nCharging that he had known in\nstances when junior high school stu\ndents had hazed members of the fresh\nman class by spraying them with a\nhose, Edward F. Worden, treasurer of\nthe association, declared that the prac\n50th ANNIVERSARY\n\nGOLDEN -y| p \u2014I SALE\nFINEST\n*lB9 FURNITURE\nRegularly $290. this custom Al 1 A I I II- C\nbuilt suite is of the finest type T. 1 flTttl 1 t ifs%=f*sSi=\nof construction, with lines that J IrA IT j I _=r=-==r_-^.-.:Jkjjiy j iRI v f A\u2014\u00ab L\u00ab\nIgpgH IN FIFTY YEARS\n_ i tomorrow\nGOLDEN II ItmUt if-r [W Since its founding fifty years ago\nJUBILEE -j |i| A I i||| |P. J. Nee Company has been known\nSolid Oak I j thrived and grown strong with\nDinette Suites Hf the continued patronage of home\n*94 i s g\u00b0\u00b0d furniture, reasonable\nprices and fair dealing... This sale,\nsJSrSff; ei.SS\u201d\u00bbi 'SS* W our first public one, aims merely at\nagular price of such a suite a* (JJ LI i i r i i i\nbringing those virtues, il they be such\ntp J Neb co.\u2014\nP** %pr WMW |V\nSeventh at H Street N.W.\ntice should cease. The matter was re\nferred to the association\u2019s Committee\non Colleges and Schools.\nLack of books in public schools also\nwas brought to the attention of the as\nsociation by Mr. Worden. This matter\nalso was referred to the association's\nCommittee \u2022on Schools and Colleges.\nTucker Elected President.\nEvan H. Tucker was elected president\nof the association for his thirty-sixth\nyear last night. Mr. Tucker took the\nchair as a president who has only\nmissed one meeting :n the 36 years of\nhis activities with the Northeast group.\nOther officers were:\nRoscoe Jenkins, first, vice president:\nBruce L. Casteel, second vice president;\nJoseph Notes, secretary John P. Callan.\nfinancial secretary, and Edward F.\nWorden, treasurer.\nCapt. Doyle Honored.\nA resolution regretting the death of\nCapt. Robert Emmett Doyle of the\nMetropolitan Police Department was\npassed by the association. The resolu\ntion pointed out that Capt. Doyle had\nbegun his police career at the ninth\nprecinct, the precinct raring for the\nneighborhood in the confines of the as\nsociation.\nAnother resolution, thank.ng Susan\nTHE EVENING STAR, TVASHTXGTOX. I). C., TUESDAY, OCTOBER 14. 1930!\nB. Rhodes, in charge of the District\nPlayground Department, for her work\nIn obtaining playgrounds for school\nchildren during the three-month va\ncation period, was pafcsM by the asso\nciation.\nA resolution asking for an addition\nto the old Patterson track, located be\ntween Fifth and Seventh streets on\nFlorida avenue, to be used as a play\nground and athletic field, was unani\nmously passed by the association.\nThe association also favored one-half\nhour parking in 24 hours in front of\nthe Post Office.\nThe new members are E. F. Glover,\nH. Clav Murray, L. D. Lefus, George\nS. Hild, Julian E. Brumley, George\nGotthardt. Frank A. PefTer. W. M.\nStaley. Mrs. Charles M. Zurhorst, J.\nHarrlein. Edward L. Rockwell. Forest\nW. Harrington. John T. Updike, R. B.\nUpdike and M. S. Fihclly.\nHalt Philippine Plan.\nMANILA (/PL\u2014 Business depression\nhas caused postpon-ment of appoint\nment of a Filipino trade commissioner\nin China. The plan was authorized to\ni help overcome present dependence upon\nthe American market\nINDUSTRIAL EXHIBIT\nHIGHLY COMMENDED\nDr. Reichelderfer Classes Cham\nber of Commerce Trade Show\nas Instructive.\nDeclaring that trade shows have been\nhighly constructive in directing public\nattention to the sound development of\nj local business and industry. Dr. Luther\nH. Reichelderfer; chairman of the Board\nI of District Commissioners, today gave\nhis indorsement to the sixth annual\nIndustrial Exposition, which will open\nNovember 3 at the Washington Audito-\nrium. under the auspices of the Wash- j\ningten Chamber of Commerce.\nIn citing the important part these\nprivate enterprises are playing in the\nprogress of Washington, Commissioner\nReichelderfer said:\n\u201cIt Ls my strong conviction that the\nvarious industrial expositions which j\nhave been held under the auspices of i\nI the Washington Chamber of Commerce\nhave done a great service In drawing\nthe attention of our people to the fact\nthat, contrary to the belief of many, the\nNational Capital ls developing very\nmaterially in an economic way.\n\u201cIndeed, the fact that we now are i\nwelcoming the advent of the sixth\nannual Industrial Exposition is ample\nproof that these exhibits are very im\nportant events in our civic calendar\u2014\nevent* to which we look forward for\ntheir graphic portrayals of the sound\nprogress of our community.\n\u2018Naturally, businesses and industries\nmust in no wav conflict with the basic\nscheme of Washington, the City Beauti- j\nful. and it is just here that the indus- j\ntrial expositions have performed a most\nnotable service. They have proved to\nus that Washington has such businesses\nand industries and that they arc grow-\nI ing steadily, surely and unobtrusively.\n\u201cIt is not only a pleasure, but in j\neffect a happy duty, for me to lend mv\nwhole-hearted indorsement to the sixth\nannual Industrial Exposition.\n\u201cIf it approaches past expositions in\ninteerst it will be successful Indeed, j\nIf, as I have been informed, it undoubt\nedly will be even more complete and j\nmore instructive than previous exhibits.\nI I believe no one in Washington will 1\nwant to miss It.\u201d\nU. S. VICTIMS OF CRASH\nIN MOROCCO IDENTIFIED\nTernill Dix. Writer, and His Wife\nLost Lives When\nplane Fell.\nBr the Associated Press.\nTOPLOUSE. France, October 14.\nTwo Americans who were killed in an\nairplane Sunday morning. near Larache.\nMorocco, were Identified today a*\nTernill Dix, a writer, and Mrs. Dix.\nFirst Book Issued Recently.\nNEW YORK, October 14 f/P).\u2014-Ternill\nDix. reported killed in an airplane\ni crash near Earache, Morocco, was the\nI son of William Frederick Dix, a vice\npresident of the Mutual Life Insurance\nI Co., whose home is at East Orange,\nThree months ago an American house\ni published the young man's first hook.\n\"The Black Baron,\" a biography of\nj oilles de Rats, the medieval \"Blue\n-1 beard.\" The father, also a writer, is\ntreasurer of the Authors Club.\nMarlboro Marriage License*.\nUPPER MARLBORO. Md October\n14.\u2014Marriage licenses have been Issued\nhere to the following:\nBenjamin Walls. jr., 23. Suttland, j\nMd., and Emma Smith, 18, Clinton,\nMd.: Earl D. Hartman, jr.. 21, and\nKittle W Gault. 18, both of Ruxton.\nMd Clifford E B\u00ab*st. 45, Seat Pleasant.\nMd and Anne E Strope. 48. New York 1\nI\nckYSE\njuiLeSIS:\ni\nThree symbols of smartness\nand thrift\nKayser Hosiery^loveS/Underthings\nLet there be rejoicing I\nI /O Kayser Hose are less!\u2014\nAll the lovely stockings of\nKayser\u2014except Sansheen*\n\u2014are reduced. Not just lit\ntie, mincing reductions, but\nY great lops that bring them\nI 1 down to the lowest prices at\nJj which they\u2019ve ever been\noffered. In the weights for\nnqOs. Fall, and the irresistible\nNA.X new Kayser shades now\nfor as little as $1.25!\nA\nKayser\u2019s lovely under-\nH II wear at lower prices\nV y Look what\u2019s happened!\nBloomers that were $4.50\n1 are now $3.95; those that\nwere $3.50 are now $2.95.\nAnd because of their ex\nY elusive Italian* pure silk\nI Marvelfit* Crotch,t these\nI sK bloomers are establishing\njr f f/~\\\\ I new endurance records.\n\\ss&d (Vests to match.)\njir''%>>\nLeatherettes* prevent\nI glove tragedy\u2014 When\nII Paris decreed \u201cFour styles\nt\\h 0 m in Gloves this season,\u201d\nljjjj |ll j budgets d